titleproper.value:
Guide to the Brian McGinn Papers
                    <num>AIA.015</num>

author.value: Finding aid prepared by Karen Murphy, Rebecca Altermatt and Kaitlyn Medley

creation.value:
This finding aid was produced using the Archivists' Toolkit
                <date>2012-03-28T15:54-0400</date>

abstract.label: Abstract
abstract.value:
Brian McGinn was a scholar of the Irish Diaspora and authors of articles on this topic. The bulk of the collection consists of McGinn’s working papers: largely photocopied sections of books (some rather rare), articles, pamphlets, monographs, and government records concerning the Irish and their migration to various parts of the world. There are photocopies of colonial records and diaries written as far back as the 16th century, and articles and correspondence through 2004. The collection also includes correspondence with other scholars of the Irish and Irish Diaspora and various archivists and librarians concerning research material. 
                <emph render="bold">NOTE: This collection is stored offsite and advance notice is required for use.</emph>

p.value:
Open for research without restrictions except for Series X and XI. See Archivist for more information. 
                <emph render="bold">NOTE: This collection is stored offsite and advance notice is required for use.</emph>

Published citations should take the following form: 
                <lb/>
                <lb/>Identification of item, date; Collection name; Collection number; box number; folder number; 
                <lb/> Archives of Irish America, Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives 
                <lb/>Elmer Holmes Bobst Library 
                <lb/>70 Washington Square South 
                <lb/>New York, NY 10012, New York University Libraries.

McGinn held an MA in Latin American Studies from Georgetown University and published extensively on the history of the Irish in Latin America. He wrote for newspapers and magazines such as the Irish Times, Irish Roots, Irish America and the Irish Echo’s IE. McGinn died on July 20, 2005, after a three-year fight with brain cancer.
<emph render="bold">NOTE: This collection is stored offsite and advance notice is required for use.</emph>
